# Mandatory Testing For Feature Changes

This rule is **framework-agnostic**. Apply the spirit of each bullet
using whichever test runner your project uses (Jest, Vitest, Pytest,
flutter_test, XCTest, JUnit, Go test, etc.).

## What to test

For any new feature, UI addition, or behavioural change, add or update
tests that cover:

- **Happy path** — the primary user-facing behaviour.
- **Edge / error states** — empty input, large input, error paths,
  boundary values, async failures.
- **Regression risk** — anything else the touched flow could break.
  If you changed a shared util/component, write at least one test for
  every direct caller you can identify.

## Verification before declaring done

- Run all newly added or updated tests and confirm they pass.
- Run tests for any dependent module/feature you touched indirectly
  (don't rely on CI to find your breakage).
- Run a static analyser / linter / type-checker pass too if the
  project has one (e.g. `dart analyze`, `tsc --noEmit`, `mypy`,
  `cargo check`).

## When you can't run tests locally

If test execution is blocked by environment or tooling, your final
message MUST clearly state:

1. What you attempted.
2. What failed (exact error or symptom).
3. The exact commands the user (or CI) needs to run to verify.

Never silently mark work complete with unverified tests.

## Definition of done

Work is not done until:

- [ ] Tests for the new behaviour exist and pass.
- [ ] Tests for at least one realistic edge case exist and pass.
- [ ] Tests for affected dependent areas exist and pass.
- [ ] Static analysis / lints are clean for the touched files.
